      "content": "thanks, that makes sense. smart pointers would definitely be safer. \n\none thing though, in my actual code it's a bit more complicated. i'm passing these buffers into a processing queue that runs on a different thread. sometimes the memory clears up, but sometimes it just vanishes or keeps climbing. it's super hard to track down who actually owns the pointer once it hits the queue. \n\ncould you show me how to handle passing a `unique_ptr` into a thread-safe queue so i don't accidentally end up with more leaks?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Passing `unique_ptr` instances to a thread-safe queue can be a bit tricky, but there are a few approaches you can take. One common solution is to use `std::shared_ptr` instead of `unique_ptr`, which allows multiple owners to share the same underlying memory.\n\nHowever, in your case, since you're dealing with a queue that's designed to process data from multiple threads, using `std::shared_ptr` might not be the best approach. This is because `std::shared_ptr` will increment the reference count every time it's accessed, which could lead to performance issues and even crashes if the queue is very busy.\n\nA better approach might be to use `std::unique_ptr` itself, but to create a wrapper class that manages the lifetime of the `unique_ptr` instance. This wrapper class can be designed to be thread-safe, and it can handle the case where the `unique_ptr` instance is copied or moved.\n\nHere's an example of how you could implement such a wrapper class:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <memory>\n#include <mutex>\n\nclass ThreadSafeUniquePtr {\npublic:\n    ThreadSafeUniquePtr(int* data, int size)\n        : data_(data), size_(size",
